Migration to Scala 2.10.2, Akka 2.2 abd SBT 0.12.3

This commit updates Hector to use the latest Scala 2.10.2
and Akka 2.2 while switching to SBT 0.12.4

Hector compiles and runs albeit some problems. Next steps
include getting rid of dead letters in IOActor (potentially
due to sender reference) and general deprecation warnings.

Migration included the following steps:

- Upgrade SBT properties, using new xsbt-web-plugin

- Added new scalac options: -Yinline-warnings, -feature
  and -language:implicitConversions

- Upgrading to scalatest 1.9.1

- Got rid of ImmutableSortedSet in HtmlEmitter due
  to scalac bug resulting in runtime VerifyError[1]

- Hack to get rid of a scalac bug in JsClientSupport
  leading to VerifyError at runtime[2]

- Migrated imports to scala.concurrent and friends

- Importing context.dispatcher where necessary

- receive is no longer protected

- Promise.successful is now Future.successful

- Using case exception: Throwable where appropriate

- Getting rid of tell() if not necessary

- Using Try instead of Either (see RequestActor)

Armature sprite.

- Added scale in <armature> in libraries descriptor.
- Armature are now initialized by the armature descriptor in libraries.

Added InParallelDynamic behavior.

- InParallelDynamic allows to add and remove behaviors dynamically. It
will constantly execute them and remove finished ones.
- Also almost finished the prototype for ArmatureSprite …. suspens….
Fixed logging error. Yet to see if tests run.
We now have a rather ugly extraction of logging from the ReadBookmarksServlet.
Using component abstractions for dependency injection.
Properly handle the default selection in a select field.

Add overloads for selects with tuples and just objects.

So we now have overloads of selectField which take:
 - A list of objects (an implicit is needed to convert them to
   Strings for display on the client).
 - A list of (T, String) tuples where the second part is the
   String to display on the client.
 - A list of SelectableOptions, which carry the object and
   the client-side label, and may also carry any attributes
   to be applied to that option.
Add a basic select field with SelectableOptions.

Make value conversion/serialization be via instance methods.

Select boxes will require us to do these by manipulating
instance variables, rather than by using external functions.
We also eliminate the ValueSerializerType concept; this was
used so that there could be a value serializer that serialized
a superclass of the FieldValueType instead of only being
able to use one that serialized the FieldValueType directly.

We may reintroduce it later, but for now dropping the
concept makes it easier to move value serialization into
an instance method.
